{"title_page": "Kalevi Sorsa", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name                = Kalevi Sorsa\n| honorific-suffix    =\n| image               = Kalevi-Sorsa-1975 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize           =\n| smallimage          =\n| caption             = Sorsa in 1975. \n| order               =\n| office              = 34th [[Prime Minister of Finland]]<ref>{{cite web\n  |title=Governments in chronological order|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/government/history/governments-and-ministers/report/-/r/v2|publisher=Finnish government (Valtioneuvosto)|accessdate=27 March 2017\n}}</ref>\n| term_start          = 19 February 1982\n| term_end            = 30 April 1987\n| president           = [[Mauno Koivisto]]\n| predecessor         = Mauno Koivisto\n| successor           = [[Harri Holkeri]]\n| deputy              = [[Ahti Pekkala]] {{Small|(1982\u20131983)}}<br/>[[Paavo V\u00e4yrynen]] {{Small|(1983\u20131987)}}\n| term_start2         = 15 May 1977\n| term_end2           = 26 May 1979\n| president2          = [[Urho Kekkonen]]\n| predecessor2        = [[Martti Miettunen]]\n| successor2          = Mauno Koivisto\n| deputy2             = [[Johannes Virolainen]]\n| term_start3         = 4 September 1972\n| term_end3           = 13 June 1975\n| president3          = Urho Kekkonen\n| predecessor3        = [[Rafael Paasio]]\n| successor3          = [[Keijo Liinamaa]]\n| deputy3             = [[Ahti Karjalainen]]\n| office4= [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start4= 30 April 1987\n| term_end4= 31 January 1989\n| primeminister4= [[Harri Holkeri]]\n| predecessor4= [[Paavo V\u00e4yrynen]]\n| successor4= [[Pertti Paasio]]\n| term_start5= 30 November 1975\n| term_end5= 29 September 1976\n| primeminister5= [[Martti Miettunen]]\n| predecessor5= [[Olavi J. Mattila]]\n| successor5= [[Keijo Korhonen]]\n| term_start6= 23 February 1972\n| term_end6= 4 September 1972\n| primeminister6= [[Rafael Paasio]]\n| predecessor6= Olavi J. Mattila\n| successor6= Ahti Karjalainen \n| office7= [[Deputy Prime Minister of Finland]]\n| term_start7= 30 April 1987\n| term_end7= 31 January 1989\n| primeminister7= Harri Holkeri \n| predecessor7= Paavo V\u00e4yrynen \n| successor7= Pertti Paasio\n| term_start8= 30 November 1975\n| term_end8= 29 September 1976\n| primeminister8= Martti Miettunen \n| predecessor8= Olavi J. Mattila \n| successor8= Ahti Karjalainen \n| birth_name= Taisto Kalevi Sorsa\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1930|12|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Keuruu]], Finland\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2004|1|16|1930|12|21|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Helsinki]], Finland\n| nationality         = [[Finnish people|Finnish]]\n| party               = [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democratic]]\n| spouse              = Elli Irene Fate \n| relations           =\n| children            =\n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          =\n| occupation          =\n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Taisto Kalevi Sorsa''' (21 December 1930 &ndash; 16 January 2004) was a [[Finland|Finnish]] politician who served as [[Prime Minister]] of Finland three times: 1972\u20131975, 1977\u20131979 and 1982\u20131987. At the time of his death he still held the record for most days of incumbency as prime minister.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.valtioneuvosto.fi/hakemisto/ministerikortisto/ministeritiedot.asp?nro=368\n |title       = Ministerikortisto\n |publisher   = Valtioneuvosto\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503220701/http://www.valtioneuvosto.fi/hakemisto/ministerikortisto/ministeritiedot.asp?nro=368\n |archivedate = 2009-05-03\n}}</ref> He was also a long-time leader of the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland]].\n\n== Early years ==\nKalevi Sorsa was born on 21 December 1930 in [[Keuruu]]. He attended school in [[Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]] and [[Lappeenranta]].\n\nAt the age of 18, Sorsa's involvement with the SDP started in Lappeenranta. Prior to his political career, Sorsa worked in Paris for [[UNESCO]] from 1959 to 1965 and served as Secretary-General of the Finnish UNESCO board from 1965 to 1969. In the late 1960s, he also served as an official in the Ministry of Education.\n\nIn 1969, he was brought in from relative obscurity by [[Rafael Paasio]], a former [[Prime Minister of Finland]], to assume the influential post of party secretary, despite not having much previous experience of national politics.\n\nA 2008 book by historian Jukka Seppinen suggested that Sorsa was at this date already receiving support from Soviet backers in the [[KGB]].<ref>[http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000000145551.html ''Ilta Sanomat'', 23 October 2008, \"The KGB prepared the way for Kalevi Sorsa in 1969\".]</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister and Foreign Minister (1972-1989)==\n\n[[File:Kalevi Sorsa.jpg|thumb|Kalevi Sorsa in 1983, during his third and longest term as Prime Minister]]\n\n===Sorsa and domestic politics===\nSorsa was a leading political figure during the presidencies of [[Kekkonen]] and [[Mauno Koivisto|Koivisto]].<ref name=ap >Matti Huuhtanen:[https://web.archive.org/web/20140611112932/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-90258815.html Finns hold state funeral for longest serving, Cold War prime minister] (paywall) [[Associated Press]] 31 January 2004, via High Beam, retrieved 28 March 2013</ref> He served as the chairman of the Social Democratic Party from 1975 to 1987 and was [[Prime Minister of Finland]] in four cabinets for a total of ten years (1972\u20131975, 1977\u20131979, 1982\u20131983, 1983\u20131987). He remains Finland's longest-serving prime minister.\n\nAfter his premiership he served as the Speaker of the Finnish Parliament from 1989 to 1991. During his career he also served twice as [[Deputy Prime Minister of Finland|Deputy Prime Minister]], from 1975 to 1976 and from 1987 to 1989.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hx5000.sh?{hnro}=235&{kieli}=su&{haku}=kaikki\n |title       = Edustajamatrikkeli\n |publisher   = Eduskunta\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503203728/http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hx5000.sh?%7Bhnro%7D=235&%7Bkieli%7D=su&%7Bhaku%7D=kaikki\n |archivedate = 2009-05-03\n}}</ref> From 1987 to 1996, Sorsa served on the governing board of the [[Bank of Finland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.suomenpankki.fi/en/bank-of-finland/organization/board/board-members-in-the-history-of-the-bank-of-finland/\n  |title=Board Members in the history of the Bank of Finland |publisher=Bank of Finland\n}}</ref><ref name=ap /> He was also known for his participation as the convener in the economic policy seminar at [[Hotel Korpilampi]] in [[Lahnus]], [[Espoo]], in September 1977.<ref>[http://hirvasnoro.blogspot.com/2007/05/jouko-kajanoja-suomen-knne-alkoi.html?m=1 Jouko Kajanoja: Suomen k\u00e4\u00e4nne alkoi Korpilammelta] (in Finnish)</ref><ref>[https://www.korpilampi.fi/en/korpilampi-40-year-anniversary/ Hotel Korpilampi Celebrates 40 Years Of Operations]</ref>\n\nSorsa is regarded as one of Finland's most influential prime ministers, making major contributions to schools and health care, and increasing social security for families with children and pensioners. His governments strengthened the welfare state in Finland, by enacting  many reforms\u2014child care laws, longer maternity leave, the annual vacation benefit act, as well as the public health act.\n\nIn domestic politics, Sorsa had a particularly difficult relationship with [[Paavo V\u00e4yrynen]], the strong-willed head of the [[Center Party (Finland)|Center Party]]. Another notable conflict was his rivalry with young rising politician [[Paavo Lipponen]].\n\nIn June 1984, Sorsa gave a speech on \"infocracy\" (i.e. the power of the [[mass media]]) at the Social Democratic party convention. Infocracy challenges [[parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[democracy]], is unintelligent and avoids discussing social problems, he said: it takes more interest in individual politicians than political issues and is never critical of its own actions.<ref>[https://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2009/10/19/kun-sorsa-suuttui-ylelle Kun Sorsa suuttui Ylelle] ''El\u00e4v\u00e4 arkisto''. [[Yle]]. 19 October 2009. Retrieved 13 July 2017.</ref>\n\n===Sorsa and foreign affairs===\nThree times Kalevi Sorsa served as [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Finland)]]: in 1972; in 1975\u20131976; and from 1987 to 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://formin.finland.fi/public/?contentid=41366&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI |title=Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland - Ministers of Foreign Affairs |publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=30 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716073918/http://formin.finland.fi/public/?contentid=41366&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI |archive-date=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSorsa supported the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] after its creation in 1975, as well as projects to bridge the gap between the world's richest and poorest countries. In the 1970s, despite opposition from far-left parties, he championed a hard-won, free-trade agreement with the [[European Economic Community]] (EEC), which boosted ties between Finland and the countries of Western Europe.\n\nSorsa was also active in the international social democratic movement, and in the mid-1970s was elected vice-president of the [[Socialist International]].\n\nIn the late 1970s and in the 1980s the Socialist International had extensive contacts and discussion with the two leading powers of the Cold War period, the United States and the Soviet Union, on issues concerning East\u2013West relations and arms control. The Socialist International supported d\u00e9tente and disarmament agreements, such as SALT II, START and INF. They had several meetings and discussion in Washington, D.C., with President Jimmy Carter and Vice-President George Bush and with CPSU Secretaries General Leonid Brezhnev and Mikhail Gorbachev in Moscow. Sorsa led the Socialist International's delegations to these discussions.<ref>{{cite book|last=V\u00e4\u00e4n\u00e4nen|first=Pentti|year=2012|title=Purppuraruusu ja samettinyrkki|edition=1st|language=Finnish|publisher=Kellastupa|pages=192\u2013194|isbn=9789525787115}}. [[Pentti V\u00e4\u00e4n\u00e4nen]] was secretary-general of the Socialist International, 1983-1989, and was earlier an adviser to Sorsa.</ref>\n\n==Later years (1989-2004)==\n\nIn 1993, Sorsa entered the Social Democratic Party's primary elections as a presidential candidate, but was forced to withdraw after revelations of his long-standing covert relations with the Soviet leadership.<ref name=\"bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com\">[https://bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com/2016/07/01/16-december-1980-st-241108/ ''The Bukovsky Archives'', 16 December 1980* (St 241/108), K. Sorsa's 50th birthday and his work for detente and disarmament] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031755/https://bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com/2016/07/01/16-december-1980-st-241108/ |date=1 December 2017 }}.</ref><ref>Vladimir Bukovsky, ''Jugement a Moscou'', Robert Laffont: Paris, 1995, pp. 14-16.</ref>\n\nIn 1992 Kalevi Sorsa announced that he would stand in the coming 1994 presidential elections. However, documents found in the [[CPSU Central Committee]] archive in Moscow during the trial of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] indicated that Sorsa had long maintained \"confidential contacts\" with the Soviet authorities.<ref name=\"bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com\"/> When news of this information finally broke in the Finnish press,<ref>''ILTA-Sanomat'', 10 July 1993, #157, \"Nepin arkistot kertovat Sorsa miellytti Moskovaa\" (Archives show that Sorsa had Moscow's special favour).</ref> Sorsa issued a public apology and withdrew his candidacy. [[Martti Ahtisaari]] took his place as the candidate of the Social Democratic Party and won the election.\n\nHe was replaced as SDP candidate by [[Martti Ahtisaari]], Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations from 1977 to 1981, who went on to become Finnish President. Ahtisaari was supported by a small but significant group of Finnish politicians who had long been hostile to Kaleva: [[Erkki Tuomioja]], [[Lasse Lehtinen]] and [[Matti Ahde]].\n\n===Later years===\nKalevi Sorsa continued to participate in discussions of social policy until the end of his life, his last column being published posthumously.\n\nHe died of cancer on 16 January 2004 at his home in Helsinki at the age of 73.<ref name=ap /> He was survived by his wife; the couple had no children.<ref name=ap />\n\nThe Kalevi Sorsa Foundation<ref>[http://sorsafoundation.fi/en/ The Kalevi Sorsa Foundation].</ref> is a social democratic [[think tank]], established in 2005 and named in his honour.\n\n==As head of government and foreign ministry==\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]], 1972\n* [[Sorsa I Cabinet]], 1972-1975\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]], 1975-1976\n* [[Sorsa II Cabinet]], 1977-1979\n* [[Sorsa III Cabinet]], 1982-1983\n* [[Sorsa IV Cabinet]], 1983-1987\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]], 1987-1989\n\n== Honours ==\n* Commander Grand Cross in the [[Order of the White Rose of Finland]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" >{{Cite book\n  |title=The International Who's Who \n  |year=2004 \n  |publisher=Europa Publications\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\"/>\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]],<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" /> Netherlands\n* Grand Cross in the [[Order of the Falcon]], Iceland<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of the North Star]],<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" /> Sweden\n* Grand Cross in the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of the Dannebrog]],<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" /> Denmark\n* Grand Cross in the [[National Order of Merit (France)|National Order of Merit]],<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" /> France\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]],<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" /> Spain\n* Grand Cross in the [[Order of the Southern Cross]],<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" /> Brazil\n\n==See also==\n*[[Politics of Finland]]\n*[[Socialist International]]\n*[[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]]\n*[[Martti Ahtisaari]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sorsafoundation.fi/en/ Kalevi Sorsa Foundation]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=1972&ndash;1975\n|before=[[Rafael Paasio]]|after=[[Keijo Liinamaa]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=1977&ndash;1979\n|before=[[Martti Miettunen]]|after=[[Mauno Koivisto]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=1982&ndash;1987\n|before=[[Mauno Koivisto]]|after=[[Harri Holkeri]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Speaker of the Parliament of Finland]]\n|before=[[Matti Ahde]]|years=1989&ndash;1991|after=[[Esko Aho]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FinnishPrimeMinisters}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sorsa, Kalevi}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Keuruu]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Finland politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Finland]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Parliament of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1970\u201372)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1972\u201375)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1975\u201379)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1979\u201383)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1983\u201387)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1987\u201391)]]\n[[Category:Central bankers]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    =\n| name                = Kalevi Sorsa\n| honorific-suffix    =\n| image               = Kalevi-Sorsa-1975 (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize           =\n| smallimage          =\n| caption             = Sorsa in 1975. \n| order               =\n| office              = 34th [[Prime Minister of Finland]]<ref >{{cite web\n  |title=Governments in chronological order|url=http://valtioneuvosto.fi/en/government/history/governments-and-ministers/report/-/r/v2|publisher=Finnish government (Valtioneuvosto)|accessdate=27 March 2017\n}}</ref>\n| term_start          = 19 February 1982\n| term_end            = 30 April 1987\n| president           = [[Mauno Koivisto]]\n| predecessor         = Mauno Koivisto\n| successor           = [[Harri Holkeri]]\n| deputy              = [[Ahti Pekkala]] {{Small|(1982\u20131983)}}<br/>[[Paavo V\u00e4yrynen]] {{Small|(1983\u20131987)}}\n| term_start2         = 15 May 1977\n| term_end2           = 26 May 1979\n| president2          = [[Urho Kekkonen]]\n| predecessor2        = [[Martti Miettunen]]\n| successor2          = Mauno Koivisto\n| deputy2             = [[Johannes Virolainen]]\n| term_start3         = 4 September 1972\n| term_end3           = 13 June 1975\n| president3          = Urho Kekkonen\n| predecessor3        = [[Rafael Paasio]]\n| successor3          = [[Keijo Liinamaa]]\n| deputy3             = [[Ahti Karjalainen]]\n| office4= [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n| term_start4= 30 April 1987\n| term_end4= 31 January 1989\n| primeminister4= [[Harri Holkeri]]\n| predecessor4= [[Paavo V\u00e4yrynen]]\n| successor4= [[Pertti Paasio]]\n| term_start5= 30 November 1975\n| term_end5= 29 September 1976\n| primeminister5= [[Martti Miettunen]]\n| predecessor5= [[Olavi J. Mattila]]\n| successor5= [[Keijo Korhonen]]\n| term_start6= 23 February 1972\n| term_end6= 4 September 1972\n| primeminister6= [[Rafael Paasio]]\n| predecessor6= Olavi J. Mattila\n| successor6= Ahti Karjalainen \n| office7= [[Deputy Prime Minister of Finland]]\n| term_start7= 30 April 1987\n| term_end7= 31 January 1989\n| primeminister7= Harri Holkeri \n| predecessor7= Paavo V\u00e4yrynen \n| successor7= Pertti Paasio\n| term_start8= 30 November 1975\n| term_end8= 29 September 1976\n| primeminister8= Martti Miettunen \n| predecessor8= Olavi J. Mattila \n| successor8= Ahti Karjalainen \n| birth_name= Taisto Kalevi Sorsa\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1930|12|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Keuruu]], Finland\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2004|1|16|1930|12|21|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Helsinki]], Finland\n| nationality         = [[Finnish people|Finnish]]\n| party               = [[Social Democratic Party of Finland|Social Democratic]]\n| spouse              = Elli Irene Fate \n| relations           =\n| children            =\n| residence           =\n| alma_mater          =\n| occupation          =\n| profession          =\n| religion            =\n| signature           =\n| website             =\n| footnotes           =\n}}\n'''Taisto Kalevi Sorsa''' (21 December 1930 &ndash; 16 January 2004) was a [[Finland|Finnish]] politician who served as [[Prime Minister]] of Finland three times: 1972\u20131975, 1977\u20131979 and 1982\u20131987. At the time of his death he still held the record for most days of incumbency as prime minister.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.valtioneuvosto.fi/hakemisto/ministerikortisto/ministeritiedot.asp?nro=368\n |title       = Ministerikortisto\n |publisher   = Valtioneuvosto\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503220701/http://www.valtioneuvosto.fi/hakemisto/ministerikortisto/ministeritiedot.asp?nro=368\n |archivedate = 2009-05-03\n}}</ref> He was also a long-time leader of the [[Social Democratic Party of Finland]].\n\n== Early years ==\nKalevi Sorsa was born on 21 December 1930 in [[Keuruu]]. He attended school in [[Jyv\u00e4skyl\u00e4]] and [[Lappeenranta]]. \n\nAt the age of 18, Sorsa's involvement with the SDP started in Lappeenranta. Prior to his political career, Sorsa worked in Paris for [[UNESCO]] from 1959 to 1965 and served as Secretary-General of the Finnish UNESCO board from 1965 to 1969. In the late 1960s, he also served as an official in the Ministry of Education.\n\nIn 1969, he was brought in from relative obscurity by [[Rafael Paasio]], a former [[Prime Minister of Finland]], to assume the influential post of party secretary, despite not having much previous experience of national politics. \n\nA 2008 book by historian Jukka Seppinen suggested that Sorsa was at this date already receiving support from Soviet backers in the [[KGB]].<ref >[http://www.iltasanomat.fi/kotimaa/art-2000000145551.html ''Ilta Sanomat'', 23 October 2008, \"The KGB prepared the way for Kalevi Sorsa in 1969\".]</ref>\n\n==Prime Minister and Foreign Minister (1972-1989)==\n\n[[File:Kalevi Sorsa.jpg|thumb|Kalevi Sorsa in 1983, during his third and longest term as Prime Minister]]\n\n===Sorsa and domestic politics===\nSorsa was a leading political figure during the presidencies of [[Kekkonen]] and [[Mauno Koivisto|Koivisto]].<ref name=ap >Matti Huuhtanen:[https://web.archive.org/web/20140611112932/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-90258815.html Finns hold state funeral for longest serving, Cold War prime minister] (paywall) [[Associated Press]] 31 January, 2004, via High Beam, retrieved 28 March, 2013</ref> He served as the chairman of the Social Democratic Party from 1975 to 1987 and was [[Prime Minister of Finland]] in four cabinets for a total of ten years (1972\u20131975, 1977\u20131979, 1982\u20131983, 1983\u20131987). He remains Finland's longest-serving prime minister. \n\nAfter his premiership he served as the Speaker of the Finnish Parliament from 1989 to 1991. During his career he also served twice as [[Deputy Prime Minister of Finland|Deputy Prime Minister]], from 1975 to 1976 and from 1987 to 1989.<ref>{{cite web\n |url         = http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hx5000.sh?{hnro}=235&{kieli}=su&{haku}=kaikki\n |title       = Edustajamatrikkeli\n |publisher   = Eduskunta\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090503203728/http://www.eduskunta.fi/triphome/bin/hx5000.sh?%7Bhnro%7D=235&%7Bkieli%7D=su&%7Bhaku%7D=kaikki\n |archivedate = 2009-05-03\n}}</ref> From 1987 to 1996, Sorsa served on the governing board of the [[Bank of Finland]].<ref >{{cite web|url=https://www.suomenpankki.fi/en/bank-of-finland/organization/board/board-members-in-the-history-of-the-bank-of-finland/\n  |title=Board Members in the history of the Bank of Finland |publisher=Bank of Finland\n}}</ref><ref name=ap /> He was also known for his participation as the convener in the economic policy seminar at [[Hotel Korpilampi]] in [[Lahnus]], [[Espoo]], in September 1977.<ref>[http://hirvasnoro.blogspot.com/2007/05/jouko-kajanoja-suomen-knne-alkoi.html?m=1 Jouko Kajanoja: Suomen k\u00e4\u00e4nne alkoi Korpilammelta] (in Finnish)</ref><ref>[https://www.korpilampi.fi/en/korpilampi-40-year-anniversary/ Hotel Korpilampi Celebrates 40 Years Of Operations]</ref>\n\nSorsa is regarded as one of Finland's most influential prime ministers, making major contributions to schools and health care, and increasing social security for families with children and pensioners. His governments strengthened the welfare state in Finland, by enacting  many reforms\u2014child care laws, longer maternity leave, the annual vacation benefit act, as well as the public health act.\n\nIn domestic politics, Sorsa had a particularly difficult relationship with [[Paavo V\u00e4yrynen]], the strong-willed head of the [[Center Party (Finland)|Center Party]]. Another notable conflict was his rivalry with young rising politician [[Paavo Lipponen]].\n\nIn June 1984, Sorsa gave a speech on \"infocracy\" (i.e. the power of the [[mass media]]) at the Social Democratic party convention. Infocracy challenges [[parliamentary system|parliamentary]] [[democracy]], is unintelligent and avoids discussing social problems, he said: it takes more interest in individual politicians than political issues and is never critical of its own actions.<ref>[https://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2009/10/19/kun-sorsa-suuttui-ylelle Kun Sorsa suuttui Ylelle] ''El\u00e4v\u00e4 arkisto''. [[Yle]]. 19 October 2009. Retrieved 13 July 2017.</ref>\n\n===Sorsa and foreign affairs===\nThree times Kalevi Sorsa served as [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Finland)]]: in 1972; in 1975-1976; and from 1987 to 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://formin.finland.fi/public/?contentid=41366&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI |title=Ministry for Foreign Affairs of Finland - Ministers of Foreign Affairs |publisher=Valtioneuvosto.fi |accessdate=30 January 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716073918/http://formin.finland.fi/public/?contentid=41366&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI |archive-date=16 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSorsa supported the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] after its creation in 1975, as well as projects to bridge the gap between the world's richest and poorest countries. In the 1970s, despite opposition from far-left parties, he championed a hard-won, free-trade agreement with the [[European Economic Community]] (EEC), which boosted ties between Finland and the countries of Western Europe.\n\nSorsa was also active in the international social democratic movement, and in the mid-1970s was elected vice-president of the [[Socialist International]]. \n\nIn the late 1970s and in the 1980s the Socialist International had extensive contacts and discussion with the two leading powers of the Cold War period, the United States and the Soviet Union, on issues concerning East\u2013West relations and arms control. The Socialist International supported d\u00e9tente and disarmament agreements, such as SALT II, START and INF. They had several meetings and discussion in Washington, D.C., with President Jimmy Carter and Vice-President George Bush and with CPSU Secretaries General Leonid Brezhnev and Mikhail Gorbachev in Moscow. Sorsa led the Socialist International's delegations to these discussions.<ref>{{cite book|last=V\u00e4\u00e4n\u00e4nen|first=Pentti|year=2012|title=Purppuraruusu ja samettinyrkki|edition=1st|language=Finnish|publisher=Kellastupa|pages=192\u2013194|isbn=9789525787115}}. [[Pentti V\u00e4\u00e4n\u00e4nen]] was secretary-general of the Socialist International, 1983-1989, and was earlier an adviser to Sorsa.</ref>\n\n==Later years (1989-2004)==\n\nIn 1993, Sorsa entered the Social Democratic Party's primary elections as a presidential candidate, but was forced to withdraw after revelations of his long-standing covert relations with the Soviet leadership.<ref >[https://bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com/2016/07/01/16-december-1980-st-241108/ ''The Bukovsky Archives'', 16 December 1980* (St 241/108), K. Sorsa's 50th birthday and his work for detente and disarmament] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031755/https://bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com/2016/07/01/16-december-1980-st-241108/ |date=1 December 2017 }}.</ref><ref>Vladimir Bukovsky, ''Jugement a Moscou'', Robert Laffont: Paris, 1995, pp. 14-16.</ref> \n\nIn 1992 Kalevi Sorsa announced that he would stand in the coming 1994 presidential elections. However, documents found in the [[CPSU Central Committee]] archive in Moscow during the trial of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] indicated that Sorsa had long maintained \"confidential contacts\" with the Soviet authorities.<ref >[https://bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com/2016/07/01/16-december-1980-st-241108/ ''The Bukovsky Archives'', 16 December 1980* (St 241/108), K. Sorsa's 50th birthday and his work for detente and disarmament] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031755/https://bukovskyarchive.wordpress.com/2016/07/01/16-december-1980-st-241108/ |date=1 December 2017 }}.</ref> When news of this information finally broke in the Finnish press,<ref >''ILTA-Sanomat'', 10 July 1993, #157, \"Nepin arkistot kertovat Sorsa miellytti Moskovaa\" (Archives show that Sorsa had Moscow's special favour).</ref> Sorsa issued a public apology and withdrew his candidacy. [[Martti Ahtisaari]] took his place as the candidate of the Social Democratic Party and won the election.\n\nHe was replaced as SDP candidate by [[Martti Ahtisaari]], Deputy Secretary-General of the United Nations from 1977 to 1981, who went on to become Finnish President. Ahtisaari was supported by a small but significant group of Finnish politicians who had long been hostile to Kaleva: [[Erkki Tuomioja]], [[Lasse Lehtinen]] and [[Matti Ahde]].\n\n===Later years===\nKalevi Sorsa continued to participate in discussions of social policy until the end of his life, his last column being published posthumously. \n\nHe died of cancer on 16 January 2004 at his home in Helsinki at the age of 73.<ref name=ap /> He was survived by his wife; the couple had no children.<ref name=ap />\n\nThe Kalevi Sorsa Foundation<ref>[http://sorsafoundation.fi/en/ The Kalevi Sorsa Foundation].</ref> is a social democratic [[think tank]], established in 2005 and named in his honour.\n\n==As head of government and foreign ministry==\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]], 1972\n* [[Sorsa I Cabinet]], 1972-1975\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]], 1975-1976\n* [[Sorsa II Cabinet]], 1977-1979\n* [[Sorsa III Cabinet]], 1982-1983\n* [[Sorsa IV Cabinet]], 1983-1987\n* [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]], 1987-1989\n\n== Honours ==\n* Commander Grand Cross in the [[Order of the White Rose of Finland]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" >{{Cite book\n  |title=The International Who's Who \n  |year=2004 \n  |publisher=Europa Publications\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\"/>\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of Orange-Nassau]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />, Netherlands\n* Grand Cross in the [[Order of the Falcon]], Iceland<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of the North Star]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />, Sweden\n* Grand Cross in the [[Order of Merit of the Republic of Poland]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of the Dannebrog]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />, Denmark\n* Grand Cross in the [[National Order of Merit (France)|National Order of Merit]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />, France\n* Knight Grand Cross in the [[Order of Isabella the Catholic]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />, Spain\n* Grand Cross in the [[Order of the Southern Cross]]<ref name=\"Whos Who, 2004\" />, Brazil\n\n==See also==\n*[[Politics of Finland]]\n*[[Socialist International]]\n*[[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Finland)]]\n*[[Martti Ahtisaari]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sorsafoundation.fi/en/ Kalevi Sorsa Foundation]\n\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=1972&ndash;1975\n|before=[[Rafael Paasio]]|after=[[Keijo Liinamaa]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=1977&ndash;1979\n|before=[[Martti Miettunen]]|after=[[Mauno Koivisto]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Prime Minister of Finland]]|years=1982&ndash;1987\n|before=[[Mauno Koivisto]]|after=[[Harri Holkeri]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Speaker of the Parliament of Finland]]\n|before=[[Matti Ahde]]|years=1989&ndash;1991|after=[[Esko Aho]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{FinnishPrimeMinisters}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sorsa, Kalevi}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Keuruu]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Finland politicians]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Deputy Prime Ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Foreign Affairs of Finland]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Parliament of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1970\u201372)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1972\u201375)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1975\u201379)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1979\u201383)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1983\u201387)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1987\u201391)]]\n[[Category:Central bankers]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1975-1976 \u2192 1975\u20131976", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalevi_Sorsa"}
{"title_page": "2020 United States presidential election in Florida", "text_new": "{{main|2020 United States presidential election}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2020 [[United States presidential election]] in Florida\n| country = Florida\n| type = presidential\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2016 United States presidential election in Florida\n| previous_year     = 2016\n| election_date = November 3, 2020\n| next_election     = 2024 United States presidential election in Florida\n| next_year         = 2024\n| turnout = %\n| image_size = \n\n| image1 = Donald Trump official portrait (cropped).jpg\n| nominee1 = [[Donald Trump]]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| home_state1 = [[Florida]]\n| running_mate1 = [[Mike Pence]]\n| electoral_vote1 =\n| popular_vote1 = \n| percentage1 = \n\n| image2 = Joe Biden 2013.jpg\n| nominee2 = [[Joe Biden]]\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| home_state2 = [[Delaware]]\n| running_mate2 = TBA\n| electoral_vote2 =\n| popular_vote2 = \n| percentage2 = \n\n| title = President\n| before_election = [[Donald Trump]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = TBA\n| after_party = \n}}\n{{ElectionsFL}}\n\nThe '''2020 United States presidential election in Florida''' is scheduled to take place on Tuesday, November 3, 2020, as part of the [[2020 United States elections]] in which all 50 states plus the [[Washington, D.C.|District of Columbia]] will participate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-elections-key-dates-midterms-2020-presidential-house-congress-senate-a8472821.html|title=US elections key dates: When are the 2018 midterms and the 2020 presidential campaign?|last=Kelly|first=Ben|date=August 13, 2018|work=[[The Independent]]|access-date=January 3, 2019}}</ref> [[Florida]] voters will choose electors to represent them in the [[United States Electoral College|Electoral College]] via a popular vote. The state of Florida has 29 electoral votes in the Electoral College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/federal-register/electoral-college/allocation.html|title=Distribution of Electoral Votes|last=|first=|date=|website=[[National Archives and Records Administration]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Miami Beach, Florida]], which hosted the [[1972 Democratic National Convention]], was a finalist to host the [[2020 Democratic National Convention]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/miami-beach/article213670709.html|title=Cruise ship hotels, zoo parties and an NBA arena: Miami's Democratic convention pitch|work=miamiherald|access-date=July 1, 2018}}</ref> The other finalists were Milwaukee and Houston. Milwaukee was ultimately decided as the host.<ref name=\":0FL\">{{Cite news|url=https://fox6now.com/2018/06/20/city-of-milwaukee-named-as-1-of-3-finalists-to-host-2020-dnc-convention/|title=City of Milwaukee 1 of 3 finalists to host 2020 Democratic National Convention|date=2018-06-20|work=FOX6Now.com|access-date=2018-07-01|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/08/22/dnc-team-visiting-milwaukee-2020-democratic-convention-site/1065267002/|title=Selection committee for 2020 Democratic Convention will visit Milwaukee next week|last=Glauber|first=Bill|date=August 22, 2018|work=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFlorida will also be incumbent president Donald Trump's home state for this election, after having identified New York as his home in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/31/us/politics/trump-new-york-florida-primary-residence.html|title=Trump, Lifelong New Yorker, Declares Himself a Resident of Florida|last=Haberman|first=Maggie|date=November 4, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=}}</ref> As a result, Trump became the first nominee of either major party to be from Florida.\n\n==Primary elections==\nThe primary elections were held on March 17, 2020.\n\n===Republican primary===\nThe Florida secretary of state declared [[Rocky de la Fuente]] to be a major candidate and thus worthy of automatic inclusion on the ballot.\n \n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Republican primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n===Democratic primary===\nThree Democrats were still in race by the time Florida held its primaries: [[Vermont]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[Bernie Sanders]], former [[Vice President of the United States|vice president]] [[Joe Biden]], and [[United States House of Representatives|Representative]] from [[Hawaii]] [[Tulsi Gabbard]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Kate |title=Elizabeth Warren Formally Announces 2020 Presidential Bid in Lawrence, Mass. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/09/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-2020.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=The New York Times |date=9 February 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zhou |first1=Li |title=Kamala Harris announces her historic 2020 presidential campaign |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/1/21/18175628/kamala-harris-2020-campaign-president |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=Vox |date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Detrow |first1=Scott |title=Cory Booker Makes It Official: He's Running For President In 2020 |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/02/01/676578945/cory-booker-makes-it-official-hes-running-for-president-in-2020 |accessdate=10 February 2019 |publisher=NPR |date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe first Democratic debate took place in [[Miami]] over two nights at the end of June 2019. It was broadcast on several of the [[NBC]] networks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/first-democratic-debate-2020-election|title=First Democratic Debate 2019: Highlights, candidates and more|website=NBC News}}</ref>\n\n{{excerpt|2020 Florida Democratic primary|fragment=FLresults}}\n\n==General election==\n===Predictions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Source\n!Ranking\n!As of\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[The Cook Political Report]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cookpolitical.com/sites/default/files/2020-03/EC%20030920.4.pdf|title=2020 POTUS Race ratings|website=The Cook Political Report|language=en|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|March 9, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Stuart Rothenberg|Inside Elections]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideelections.com/ratings/president|title=POTUS Ratings {{!}} Inside Elections|website=insideelections.com|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|April 3, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Sabato's Crystal Ball]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://centerforpolitics.org/crystalball/2020-president/|title=Larry J. Sabato's Crystal Ball \u00bb 2020 President|website=crystalball.centerforpolitics.org|access-date=2019-05-21}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Lean|R}}\n|April 2, 2020\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Politico]]<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.politico.com/2020-election/race-forecasts-and-predictions/president/ |title=2020 Election Forecast|date=November 19, 2019 |publisher=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n|{{USRaceRating|Tossup}}\n|November 19, 2019\n|}\n\n===Polling===\n====Aggregate polls====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!colspan=\"7\"|Donald Trump vs. Joe Biden\n|-\n!Source of poll aggregation\n!Dates administered\n!Dates updated\n![[Joe Biden]]\n![[Donald Trump]]\n!Other/Undecided{{Efn|Calculated by taking the difference of 100% and all other candidates combined.|name=|group=}}\n!Margin\n|-\n|[https://www.270towin.com/2020-polls-biden-trump/florida/ 270 to Win]\n|March 16, 2020 - April 6, 2020\n|April 6, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''45.5%'''\n|44.0%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|{{hs|1.5}}'''Biden + 1.5'''\n|-\n|[https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/fl/florida_trump_vs_biden-6841.html Real Clear Politics]\n|March 5, 2020 \u2013 April 4, 2020\n|April 4, 2020\n|{{party shading/Democratic}}|'''46.7%'''\n|46.3%\n|\n|{{party shading/Democr