mtv.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10312~5878,00.html Huddersfield Town profile]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{ESPNsoccernet}}\n\n{{West Bromwich Albion F.C. Player of the Season}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wallwork, Ronnie}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Manchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Carlisle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ashton United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:People convicted of theft]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of England and Wales]]\n[[Category:English prisoners and detainees]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|           name = Ronnie Wallwork\n|          image = Wallwork, Ronnie.jpg\n|        caption = Wallwork in 2007\n|       fullname = Ronald Wallwork<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|20402|accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n|     birth_date = {{birth date and age|1977|9|10|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n|    birth_place = [[Manchester]], England\n|         height = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref name=PremProfile/>\n|       position = [[Midfielder]]<ref name=Hugman/>\n|    currentclub = [[Ashton United F.C.|Ashton United]] \n|    youthyears1 = 1993\u20131995 |youthclubs1 = [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester United]]\n|         years1 = 1995\u20132002 |clubs1  = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]          |caps1  = 19 |goals1  = 0\n|         years2 = 1997\u20131998 |clubs2  = \u2192 [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] (loan)     |caps2  = 10 |goals2  = 1\n|         years3 = 1998      |clubs3  = \u2192 [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]] (loan)   |caps3  = 7  |goals3  = 0\n|         years4 = 1999      |clubs4  = \u2192 [[Royal Antwerp FC|Royal Antwerp]] (loan)           |caps4  = 17 |goals4  = 2\n|         years5 = 2002\u20132008 |clubs5  = [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]    |caps5  = 93 |goals5  = 2\n|         years6 = 2004      |clubs6  = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)       |caps6  = 5  |goals6  = 2\n|         years7 = 2004      |clubs7  = \u2192 [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] (loan)       |caps7  = 2  |goals7  = 2\n|         years8 = 2006      |clubs8  = \u2192 [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] (loan)                   |caps8  = 2  |goals8  = 0\n|         years9 = 2007      |clubs9  = \u2192 [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] (loan) |caps9  = 16 |goals9  = 3\n|        years10 = 2008      |clubs10 = [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]      |caps10 = 7  |goals10 = 0\n|        years11 = 2014\u2013     |clubs11 = [[Ashton United F.C.|Ashton United]]                  |caps11 =    |goals11 = \n|      totalcaps = 178       |totalgoals = 12\n| nationalyears1 = 1997 |nationalteam1 = [[England national under-20 football team|England U20]] |nationalcaps1 = 4 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n}}\n'''Ronald Wallwork''' (born 10 September 1977) is an English former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[midfielder]].\n\nAn [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20]] international, he began his career at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], where he made his professional debut in 1997. He never fully established himself in the United first-team however, and was [[loan (football)|loaned]] out to [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] and [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]. During a further loan spell at [[Royal Antwerp FC|Royal Antwerp]], he was banned from football for life for attacking a Belgian [[referee (association football)|referee]], although the ban was later substantially reduced.\n\nIn 2002, Wallwork moved to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], where he was the Player of the Year for [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]]. He was not always a regular in the side however, and spent time on loan at [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]], [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] and [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. His spell at Barnsley was cut short when he was [[stabbed]] in a nightclub, causing him to miss more than two months of the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]] season. Wallwork was transferred to [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] in January 2008, but was released just four months later. In December 2011, he was sentenced to 15 months in prison after he pleaded guilty to three counts of receiving stolen goods. He returned to football in 2014 signing for [[Ashton United F.C.|Ashton United]].\n\n==Career==\n===Manchester United===\nBorn in [[Manchester]], Greater Manchester,<ref name=Hugman/> Wallwork attended [[The Football Association]]'s School of Excellence at [[Lilleshall Hall|Lilleshall]] as a teenager.<ref>{{cite news |title=Clement pays Ronnie emotional tribute |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~666894,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=20 May 2005 |accessdate=17 June 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> A lifelong [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] supporter, he joined the club as an apprentice in April 1993, following a spell playing [[Sunday league football]].<ref name=\"WBA Whos Who\">{{cite book |last=Matthews |first=Tony |title=The Who's Who of West Bromwich Albion |publisher=Breedon Books |year=2005 |pages=237\u2013238 |isbn=1-85983-474-4 }}</ref><ref name=\"Sunday league\">{{cite web |title=Ex-Reds: Jonathan Greening and Ronnie Wallwork |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={B4CEE8FA-9A47-47BC-B069-3F7A2F35DB70}&newsid=314355&page=3 |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=17 March 2006 |accessdate=13 July 2008 }}</ref> Wallwork signed his first trainee contract in July 1994, before turning professional in March 1995.<ref name=\"WBA Whos Who\"/> He became a regular in the Manchester United junior sides, making 77 appearances for the club's various youth teams from 1994 to 1997. Wallwork helped United to win the [[FA Youth Cup]] in 1995 and was named as the club's Young Player of the Year in 1996.<ref name=\"WBA Whos Who\"/><ref name=\"ShropshireStar\">{{cite news |title=Footballer hurt in stab attack |url=http://www.shropshirestar.com/2006/12/01/footballer-hurt-in-stab-attack/ |newspaper=Shropshire Star |location=Telford |date=1 December 2006 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref> In the summer of 1997, he represented the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20]] team at the [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship]] in [[Malaysia]], where he played in all four of his country's matches. England won all three group games to progress to the knockout stages but lost to Argentina in the [[round of 16]].<ref name=\"FIFA.com\">{{cite web |title=FIFA Player Statistics: Ronald WALLWORK |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/statisticsandrecords/players/player=176569/index.html |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=13 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=250px|align=left|quote=\"I've been a Red all my life and I used to stand on the Stretford End, so to get picked to play for the team you love is an honour. I'd been playing Sunday league football when United came in for me.\"|source='''Ronnie Wallwork'''<ref name=\"Sunday league\"/>}}\n\nBy the start of the [[1997\u201398 in English football|1997\u201398 season]], he had become a regular in the Manchester United reserve team and made his senior debut on 25 October 1997, when he came on as a 64th-minute substitute for [[Gary Pallister]] in the 7\u20130 home win against [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork glad to back in action |url=http://www.examiner.co.uk/huddersfield-town-fc/huddersfield-town-news/2007/10/06/wallwork-glad-to-back-in-action-86081-19902133/ |newspaper=Huddersfield Daily Examiner |date=6 October 2007 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref> Later that season, Wallwork was loaned out twice: firstly to [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]], where he scored his first goal in professional football, and then to [[Stockport County F.C.|Stockport County]]. He joined [[Royal Antwerp FC|Royal Antwerp]] on loan during the following season and helped them to reach the play-offs, but their hopes of promotion to the [[Belgian First Division|First Division]] were ended by a defeat to [[R.A.A. Louvi\u00e9roise|La Louvi\u00e8re]].<ref name=\"Belgian play-offs\"/> After the match, Wallwork grabbed referee Amand Ancion by the throat, for which he was banned from football for life.<ref>{{cite news |title=Life ban for Man Utd hopeful |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/410955.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=3 August 1999 |accessdate=24 June 2008 }}</ref> Another Manchester United loanee, [[Danny Higginbotham]], was banned for a year for his part in the attack. A Belgian court reduced Wallwork's sentence to a three-year suspension, of which two years were probational, while Higginbotham's ban was reduced to four months.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork life-ban dropped |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sport/football/450437.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 September 1999 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref> The remaining twelve months of Wallwork's ban applied only in Belgium, rather than the worldwide ban given under the initial ruling.<ref>{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Mathieson |title=Antwerp link flourishing |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_united/s/1059898_antwerp_link_flourishing |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=25 July 2008 |accessdate=29 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000 season]] saw Wallwork make further progress at Manchester United as he made seven appearances for the first-team, mostly as a defensive midfielder. Then, in [[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301]], he amassed enough league appearances to qualify for a [[Premier League]] winner's medal.<ref name=\"ShropshireStar\"/> However, his spell in the United first-team was short-lived, as the signings of centre-back [[Laurent Blanc]] and central midfielder [[Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n]] made Wallwork surplus to requirements. He made his final appearance for United on 26 January 2002, playing 61 minutes of the [[FA Cup]] Fourth Round match against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] before being replaced by [[Ryan Giggs]]. In his seven years at United, Wallwork played just 28 times, and in the summer of 2002 his contract was not renewed.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork mulls Baggies offer |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/2041263.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=12 June 2002 |accessdate=13 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===West Bromwich Albion===\n{{Quote box|width=275px|align=right|quote=\"Ronnie is the best Bosman transfer of the summer [of 2002]. He was a marvellous player at Old Trafford but he was unfortunate that he never had a set position. He came here as a promising young centre-half, we farmed him out to get him some experience, and ended up playing him in a variety of positions, all of which he did well in.\" |source='''[[Alex Ferguson]]'''<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Lansley |title=Fergie sets up Old Trafford fortress |url=http://www.sportinglife.com/football/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer/02/08/16/manual_072930.html |website=SportingLife.com |publisher=365 Media Group |date=16 August 2002 |accessdate=5 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605013107/http://www.sportinglife.com/football/news/story_get.cgi?STORY_NAME=soccer%2F02%2F08%2F16%2Fmanual_072930.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>}}\nIn July 2002, Wallwork moved on to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] on a [[Bosman ruling|Bosman free transfer]], becoming the first player signed by Albion following their [[promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork makes Baggies move |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/2067670.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=1 July 2002 |accessdate=23 April 2007 }}</ref> Manchester United manager Sir [[Alex Ferguson]] called him the \"best Bosman of the summer\".<ref>{{cite news |first=Peter |last=Lansley |title=Wallwork happy to acknowledge debt to Ferguson |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,3165-2091598,00.html |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=18 March 2006 |accessdate=13 January 2008 }}</ref> Before the season started, Wallwork and his Albion teammates were involved in a dispute over bonuses with the club's new [[board of directors]]. According to his agent, the player was said to be \"shocked and disturbed\" at the prospect of an 80% reduction in bonuses compared with that offered by the outgoing board.<ref>{{cite news |title=PFA set to step in |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/2159751.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=29 July 2002 |accessdate=5 August 2008 }}</ref> Wallwork made his Albion debut as a substitute in a 3\u20131 home defeat to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 24 August,<ref>{{cite news |title=WBA vs Leeds United |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~17982,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120426174201/http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~17982,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 April 2012 |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=24 August 2002 |accessdate=28 January 2008 }}</ref> and he went on to play in 27 of Albion's 38 Premier League games in [[2002\u201303 FA Premier League|2002\u201303]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronnie Wallwork career statistics 2002\u201303 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=132&playerid=8258 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=16 June 2008 }}</ref> Following the death of his mother in February 2003, he and his teammates each wore a black armband for the match against [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]].<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Simpson |title=Boss' tribute to grieving Ronnie |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~340425,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=8 February 2003 |accessdate=29 July 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The club was eventually relegated at the end of the campaign and Wallwork fell out of favour during [[2003\u201304 in English football|2003\u201304]], taking part in just five league matches during the first half of the season.<ref name=\"Stats 2003-04\">{{cite web |title=Ronnie Wallwork career statistics 2003\u201304 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=133&playerid=8258 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=16 June 2008 }}</ref> In January 2004, he joined [[Bradford City A.F.C.|Bradford City]] on an initial month-long loan, during which time he scored in his first and last games.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradford get Wallwork |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/3410859.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=21 January 2004 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nine wins to beat drop! |url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/1/26/103714.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130422052608/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/1/26/103714.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=22 April 2013 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |location=Bradford |date=26 January 2004 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork's fate unclear |url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/2/23/102775.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505140110/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/2/23/102775.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |location=Bradford |date=23 February 2004 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref> Albion initially refused an extension to the loan, citing concerns over the financial situation at Bradford, who were on the verge of [[administration (law)|administration]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork back at West Brom |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/3518295.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=24 February 2004 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref> A second loan deal for a further two months at Bradford was agreed shortly afterwards,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork in Bradford return |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/bradford_city/3490956.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=26 February 2004 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref> and Wallwork scored a further two goals, taking his total with Bradford to four in seven games.<ref name=\"Stats 2003-04\"/> He attributed his new-found goalscoring form to tactical instructions from manager [[Bryan Robson]], who told him to get forward more often, in contrast to his deeper-lying role at West Bromwich Albion.<ref>{{cite news |first=Rob |last=Stewart |title=Wallwork gets goal habit |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2374429/Wallwork-gets-goal-habit.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=7 March 2004 |accessdate=5 August 2008 }}</ref> A broken toe sustained in a match against [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] meant that he returned earlier than scheduled, however.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Wallwork back at Hawthorns |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/3548191.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2004 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Player exodus sounded death knell for City |url=http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/4/22/101218.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505081230/http://archive.thetelegraphandargus.co.uk/2004/4/22/101218.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=Telegraph & Argus |location=Bradford |date=22 April 2004 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref> While Wallwork was sidelined for six weeks, his West Bromwich Albion teammates secured promotion back to the Premier League at the first attempt.\n\nBack in the top division, Wallwork was still unable to force his way back into Albion manager [[Gary Megson]]'s matchday squad. However, when Bryan Robson \u2013 who had been Wallwork's manager at Bradford \u2013 replaced Megson in November 2004, Wallwork became an integral part of the team. Robson referred to Wallwork as \"an intelligent footballer\" who could \"sit, pass the ball and change the direction of a game\" from central midfield.<ref>{{cite news |title=Boss: More to come from Ronnie |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~609901,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=7 May 2005 |accessdate=17 June 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Wallwork returned to the team the following month and was ever-present throughout the second half of the season,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wonder Wallwork itching for more |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~665677,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=16 May 2005 |accessdate=17 June 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> scoring his first Albion goal in a 2\u20130 home win over [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 22 January 2005.<ref>{{cite news |title=WBA vs Manchester City |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~27648,00.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120426174335/http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10366~27648,00.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 April 2012 |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=22 January 2005 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref> The club successfully avoided relegation, retaining their top-flight status on the final day of the season, when they beat [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]]. Albion became the first Premier League club to avoid relegation having been bottom of the table at Christmas.<ref>{{cite news |title=West Brom 2-0 Portsmouth |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4525119.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=15 May 2005 |accessdate=17 June 2008 }}</ref> For his efforts, Wallwork was named as Albion's Player of the Year for [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305]].<ref name=\"WBA Player of the Year\">{{cite news |title=Wallwork wins Player-of-the-Year award |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~665902,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=18 May 2005 |accessdate=17 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090209014647/http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0%2C%2C10366~665902%2C00.html |archivedate=9 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In May 2005, he signed a new contract, to keep him at Albion until June 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork pens new West Brom deal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/4566723.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2005 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n{{Quote box|width=250px|align=left|quote=\"I was Player of the Year one minute at West Brom, the next I was out of the team and then out of the club. Things can change very quickly in football, it comes with the territory.\"|source='''Ronnie Wallwork'''<ref>{{Cite journal |title=The Inside Track |journal=Wednesday (Sheffield Wednesday official matchday programme) |publisher=Dunwoody, for [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] |issue=21 |page=13 |date=4 March 2008 }}</ref>}}\nThe [[2005\u201306 in English football|following season]] Wallwork played in 31 out of 38 Premier League games,<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronnie Wallwork career statistics 2005\u201306 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=135&playerid=8258 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=16 June 2008}}</ref> but was unable to prevent Albion's relegation to the [[Football League Championship|Championship]]. He nevertheless signed a new two-year deal with the club in August 2006.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronnie makes intentions clear |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~885387,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=21 August 2006 |accessdate=17 June 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He remained a regular in the side during the early part of the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307]] season, but following the appointment of Bryan Robson's successor [[Tony Mowbray]] in October, Wallwork played just once more for the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronnie Wallwork career statistics 2006\u201307 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=136&playerid=8258 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=CenturyComm |accessdate=16 June 2008 }}</ref> Mowbray described Wallwork as \"a very good professional\", but preferred a number of other midfielders ahead of him when selecting the team,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork and 'Zubi' up for loan |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~930754,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=22 November 2006 |accessdate=5 August 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> moving [[Jonathan Greening]] from a wide position into the central midfield holding role previously occupied by Wallwork.<ref>{{cite news |title=Greening driven by fear factor |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~918413,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=27 October 2006 |accessdate=5 August 2008 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In order to continue playing first-team football, Wallwork joined [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]] on loan on 22 November 2006; the loan spell was due to last until 1 January 2007, though West Bromwich Albion had a recall option after 28 days.<ref>{{cite news |title=Barnsley capture quartet on loan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/barnsley/6172052.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=23 November 2006 |accessdate=12 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 30 November 2006, Wallwork was attacked while on a night out with his girlfriend Amy Broadbent at the Sugar Lounge night club in [[Manchester]]. He was approached by a former boyfriend of Broadbent, Robert Rimmer, who asked him to leave. When Wallwork refused to do so, Rimmer used a fish knife to stab the footballer seven times in the hand, back and stomach.<ref name=\"man jailed\">{{cite news |title=Man jailed for footballer attack |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/7155931.stm |website=BBC News |date=21 December 2007 |accessdate=20 April 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork hurt after bar stabbing |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6198138.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=1 December 2006 |accessdate=27 January 2008 }}</ref> After being rushed to hospital, Wallwork's condition was said to be stable and his injuries were not thought to be life-threatening. Police investigating the stabbing described the attack as \"not random\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork 'stable' after stabbing |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/england/manchester/6201844.stm |website=BBC News |date=2 December 2006 |accessdate=17 April 2008 }}</ref> They later named 20-year-old Rimmer as the suspect and appealed for him to contact them.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wanted Man Named |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1243214,00.html |website=Sky News |date=6 December 2006 |accessdate=17 April 2008 }}</ref> Rimmer handed himself into a police station in Manchester and was arrested on 7 December.<ref>{{cite news |title=Arrest over footballer stabbing |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/6218284.stm |website=BBC News |date=7 December 2006 |accessdate=20 April 2008 }}</ref> In December 2007, Rimmer, from [[Gorton]], Manchester, was jailed for five-and-a-half years for stabbing Wallwork after admitting [[grievous bodily harm|wounding with intent]] at Manchester Crown Court. Rimmer's friend, Charles Ebbrell, a 27-year-old from [[Denton, Greater Manchester]], was given a suspended jail sentence after he admitted punching Wallwork during the attack.<ref name=\"man jailed\"/> Wallwork was released from hospital on 10 December 2006,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork released from hospital |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/6167131.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=10 December 2006 |accessdate=14 May 2008 }}</ref> the same day that Barnsley and West Bromwich Albion faced each other in a league game; Barnsley supporters displayed a \"Get well soon Ronnie\" banner during the match.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sarah |last=Holt |title=Barnsley 1-1 West Brom |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/6201410.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=10 December 2006 |accessdate=15 July 2008 }}</ref> After returning to light training in late January,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork eyes return to training |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/west_bromwich_albion/6270315.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=17 January 2007 |accessdate=13 January 2008 }}</ref> Wallwork made his comeback from the stabbing on 21 February 2007, playing the full 90 minutes in a West Bromwich Albion reserve team game against [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Walsall Res 1 Albion Res 2 |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~985708,00.htm |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=21 February 2007 |accessdate=13 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119232255/http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~985708,00.html |archivedate=19 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Huddersfield Town===\nWallwork was loaned out to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] on 27 September 2007, joining up once more with manager [[Andy Ritchie (English footballer)|Andy Ritchie]], who had brought him to Barnsley the season before.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork seals Terriers switch |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~1122233,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=28 September 2007 |accessdate=28 September 2007 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He made his Huddersfield debut in a 2\u20130 home win over [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] on 29 September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Huddersfield 2-0 Luton |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_2/7008235.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=29 September 2007 |accessdate=28 August 2012 }}</ref> On 20 October, he scored his first goal for Town in a match against [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]], which finished 1\u20131. His loan was extended by another month on 29 October. He was also given permission by West Bromwich Albion to play in Town's [[FA Cup]] first round tie against [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] on 10 November.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork's Terriers loan extended |url=http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/0,,10366~1155102,00.html |publisher=West Bromwich Albion F.C. |date=30 October 2007 |accessdate=30 October 2007 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Wallwork's loan was extended on 22 November until 29 December, the maximum loan period of 93 days permitted under league rules, when he returned to West Bromwich Albion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork's Staying 'Til Xmas |url=http://www.htafc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10312~1173453,00.html |publisher=Huddersfield Town F.C. |date=22 November 2007 |accessdate=23 November 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Sheffield Wednesday===\nOn 11 January 2008, Wallwork signed for [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] on a free transfer until the end of the season, with a view to an extension afterwards.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owls recruit Baggies man Wallwork |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_wed/7183275.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=11 January 2008 |accessdate=11 January 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork seals switch to Owls |url=http://www.teamtalk.com/football/story/0,16368,1829_3039324,00.html |publisher=TEAMtalk |date=11 January 2008 |accessdate=11 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120215959/http://www.teamtalk.com/football/story/0,16368,1829_3039324,00.html |archivedate=20 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He made his debut the following day, coming on as a half-time substitute for [[Steve Watson]] in a 1\u20130 defeat away at [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cardiff City vs Sheffield Wed |url=http://www.swfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10304~38918,00.html |publisher=Sheffield Wednesday F.C. |date=12 January 2008 |accessdate=12 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219125721/http://www.swfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10304~38918,00.html |archivedate=19 February 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He lost his place in the team to new signing [[Adam Bolder]], and although he came on as an early substitute for [[Graham Kavanagh]] against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] on 12 February 2008,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/owls/Kavanagh-to-miss-Owls39-crunch.3781775.jp |title=Kavanagh to miss Owls' crunch match |newspaper=Sheffield Star |date=15 February 2008 |accessdate=7 March 2008}}</ref> he did not play for nearly another month until his appearance in a 2\u20131 victory against [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]]. Wallwork played just seven games for Wednesday,<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronnie Wallwork career statistics 2007\u201308 |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?seasonid=137&playerid=8258 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=16 June 2008 }}</ref> who released him on 14 May 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=Wednesday release seven players |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sheff_wed/7400541.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=14 May 2008 |accessdate=14 May 2008 }}</ref> He trained with former club [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] in August 2008,<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork training with Cumbrians |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/carlisle_united/7588212.stm |website=BBC Sport |date=29 August 2008 |accessdate=29 August 2008 }}</ref> but failed to earn a permanent contract. The player \"wasn't strong enough or fit enough for the levels we're at\", according to Carlisle manager [[John Ward (footballer, born 1951)|John Ward]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ward won't wait for Wallwork |url=http://www.sportbox.tv/football/news/story.php?id=271232 |website=Sportbox.tv |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724102934/http://www.sportbox.tv/football/news/story.php?id=271232 |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, he returned to football, signing for [[Ashton United F.C.|Ashton United]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wallwork coup for Robins |url=http://www.evostikleague.co.uk/wallwork-coup-for-robins-21239/ |publisher=Northern Premier League |date=6 October 2014 |accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIn the summer of 1997, he represented the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20]] team at the [[1997 FIFA World Youth Championship]] in [[Malaysia]], where he played in all four of his country's matches. England won all three group games to progress to the knockout stages but lost to Argentina in the round of 16.<ref name=\"FIFA.com\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nWallwork runs a clothes business, D&R Designers, in [[Failsworth]], [[Greater Manchester]]. In 2007, the business was burgled, with hundreds of pounds worth of goods stolen.<ref name=\"Ronnie's bad run continues in court\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Greer |title=Ronnie's bad run continues in court |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/1090403_ronnies_bad_run_continues_in_court |newspaper=Oldham Advertiser |date=14 January 2009 |accessdate=23 January 2009 }}</ref> On 18 August 2008, Wallwork was seen to be talking on his mobile phone while driving his [[BMW 5 Series|BMW 525]], in Failsworth. He pleaded guilty to the offence five months later and was fined \u00a335, ordered to pay \u00a335 costs and a \u00a315 [[victim surcharge]], and was given three penalty points on his licence.<ref name=\"Ronnie's bad run continues in court\"/> On 18 January 2011, he was charged with concealing criminal property in connection with offences relating to stolen cars.<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Scheerhout |title=Ex-United star Ronnie Wallwork charged by police in stolen cars probe |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/crime/s/1405664_exunited_star_ronnie_wallwork_charged_by_police_in_stolen_cars_probe |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=19 January 2011 |accessdate=19 January 2011 }}</ref> On 1 July 2011, he pleaded guilty to three counts of handling stolen cars.<ref>{{cite news |first=Dean |last=Kirby |title=Former Manchester United starlet Ronnie Wallwork facing jail after pleading guilty to handling stolen cars |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/news/crime/s/1425465_former-manchester-united-starlet-ronnie-wallwork-facing-jail-after-pleading-guilty-to-handling-stolen-cars |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=1 July 2011 |accessdate=3 July 2011 }}</ref> Judge Simon Newell denied Wallwork's defence lawyer's pleas for his client to be given a suspended sentence and jailed Wallwork for 15 months on 5 December 2011. He called the set-up \"professional and sophisticated\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-16012632|title=Ronnie Wallwork jailed for 15 months |date=5 December 2011 |accessdate=5 December 2011 |website=BBC News}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n:Source:<ref>{{cite web |title=Ronnie Wallwork career statistics |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=8258 |website=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=16 June 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Spelersfiche Ronnie Wallwork |url=http://www.rafc.be/spelersfiches/spelersfiche.php?id=263%20%20%20 |publisher=Royal Antwerp F.C. |language=Dutch |accessdate=28 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080102142556/http://www.rafc.be/spelersfiches/spelersfiche.php?id=263%20%20%20 |archivedate=2 January 2008 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><!--Preceding reference contains a direct link. To view the page in context of the site, go to http://www.rafc.be/eng/index2.html and click \"Manchester UTD\" - \"Players\" - \"Ronnie Wallwork\" --><ref>{{cite web |title=Royal Antwerp Football Club Uitslagen & Rangschikking 1998\u20131999 |url=http://www.rafc.be/seizoensarchief/rangschikking.php?seizoen=1998-1999 |publisher=Royal Antwerp F.C. |language=Dutch |accessdate=28 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070112201956/http://www.rafc.be/seizoensarchief/rangschikking.php?seizoen=1998-1999 |archivedate=12 January 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><!--Preceding reference contains a direct link. To view the page in context of the site, go to http://www.rafc.be/eng/index2.html and click \"History\" - \"Overall Standings\" - \"1998 - 1999\" --><ref name=