ame=PremProfile>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/922/Ronnie-Wallwork/overview |title=Ronnie Wallwork: Overview |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=10 November 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: [[1999 Intercontinental Cup|1999]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyota99.html |title=Intercontinental Club Cup 1999 |first1=Karel |last1=Stokkermans |first2=Marcos Cabaleiro |last2=P\u00e9rez |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=13 February 2005 |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*[[Jimmy Murphy Young Player of the Year]]: [[1995\u201396 Manchester United F.C. season|1995\u201396]]<ref name=\"ShropshireStar\"/>\n*[[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] Player of the Year: [[2004\u201305 West Bromwich Albion F.C. season|2004\u201305]]<ref name=\"WBA Player of the Year\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080116063311/http://www.swfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10304~5878,00.html Sheffield Wednesday profile]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071008132654/http://www.wba.premiumtv.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10366~5878,00.html West Bromwich Albion profile]\n*[http://www.htafc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/ProfilesDetail/0,,10312~5878,00.html Huddersfield Town profile]\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{ESPNsoccernet}}\n\n{{West Bromwich Albion F.C. Player of the Season}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wallwork, Ronnie}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Manchester]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Manchester United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Carlisle United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Stockport County F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Royal Antwerp F.C. players]]\n[[Category:West Bromwich Albion F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Bradford City A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Barnsley F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Huddersfield Town A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Wednesday F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Ashton United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in Belgium]]\n[[Category:People convicted of theft]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of England and Wales]]\n[[Category:English prisoners and detainees]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer statistics:Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronnie_Wallwork"}
{"title_page": "Alfons De Wolf", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Alfons De Wolf\n| image         =\n| fullname      = Alfons De Wolf\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1956|6|22}}\n| birth_place   = [[Willebroek]], Belgium\n| currentteam   = Retired\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     = Classics specialist\n| amateuryears1 = 1978\n| amateurteam1  = {{ct|IJsboerke|1979}} ''(stagiaire)''\n| proyears1     = 1979\u20131980\n| proteam1      = {{ct|Boule d'Or|1979}}\n| proyears2     = 1981\u20131982\n| proteam2      = {{ct|Vermeer Thijs|1981}}\n| proyears3     = 1983\n| proteam3      = {{ct|Bianchi|1983}}\n| proyears4     = 1984\n| proteam4      = {{ct|Europ Decor|1984}}\n| proyears5     = 1985\n| proteam5      = {{ct|Fagor2|1985}}\n| proyears6     = 1986\n| proteam6      = Skala\u2013Skil\n| proyears7     = 1987\u20131989\n| proteam7      = {{ct|AD Renting|1987}}\n| proyears8     = 1990\n| proteam8      = {{ct|Tulip|1990}}\n| majorwins     = [[Giro di Lombardia]] ([[1980 Giro di Lombardia|1980]])<br>[[Milan\u2013San Remo]] ([[1981 Milan\u2013San Remo|1981]])<br>[[Tour de France]], 1 stage<br>[[Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a]], 5 stages<br>\n:Points classification ([[1979 Vuelta a Espa\u00f1a|1979]])\n}}\n'''Alfons (\"Fons\") De Wolf''' (born 22 June 1956 in [[Willebroek]]) is a retired [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[bicycle racing|road race cyclist]], a professional from 1979 to 1990. He represented his country at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]] in [[Montreal, Quebec]], Canada.<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/de/fons-de-wolf-1.html |title=Alfons De Wolf Olympic Results |accessdate=22 April 2015 |work=Sports Reference}}</ref>\n\nHe was forecast, with [[Daniel Willems]], to be the successor to [[Eddy Merckx]]. De Wolf seemed to fulfill that promise by having an absolutely dominant [[1979 Vuelta a Espana]] winning 5 stages including an individual time trial as well as the Points Classification, securing a top 10 place in the General Classification and then following it up by winning the 1980 [[Giro di Lombardia]] and the 1981 [[Milan\u2013San Remo]], the last and first classic of the season. He almost won the 1982 [[Li\u00e8ge\u2013Bastogne\u2013Li\u00e8ge]], beaten by Italian [[Silvano Contini]] in the final sprint.\n\nAfter winning a stage in the 1984 [[Tour de France]], his career faded. He helped his teammate [[Eddy Planckaert]] win the [[green jersey]] in the [[1988 Tour de France]]. He ended his career in 1990.\n\nHe now helps his wife in her funeral parlour in [[Dworp]], in the south of [[Brussels]].\n\nAlthough he won the [[Omloop Het Nieuwsblad|Omloop Het Volk]] two times, De Wolf was an atypical Flemish cyclist, preferring Italian races such as Milan\u2013San Remo to [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]], [[Gent\u2013Wevelgem]] and the [[Tour of Flanders]]. He was at ease in hilly races, though he was not an impressive climber.\n\nHe complained that he was seen as a 'new Eddy Merckx', that the public had expected too much.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;1976\n: 1st Tour de Namur\n: 3rd [[Ronde van Vlaanderen Beloften]]\n: 4th [[Cycling at the 1976 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's individual road race|Road race]], [[1976 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]]\n;1977\n: 1st [[Kattekoers]]\n: 3rd [[Ronde van Vlaanderen Beloften]]\n;1978\n: 1st [[Paris\u2013Roubaix Espoirs]]\n: 1st [[File:MaillotB\u00e9lgica.svg|20px]] [[Belgian National Road Race Championships|Road race]], National Amateur Road Championships\n: 2nd Overall [[GP Tell]]\n: 2nd [[Circuit de Wallonie]]\n: 2nd [[Fl\u00e8che Ardennaise]]\n: 2nd [[Kattekoers]]\n;1979\n: 1st Omloop Schelde-Durme\n: 2nd [[Trofeo Baracchi]] (with [[Jan van Houwelingen (cyclist)|Jan van Houwelingen]])\n: 2nd Leeuwse Pijl\n: 3rd Overall [[Tour of Belgium]]\n: 3rd [[Scheldeprijs]]\n: 4th Overall [[Three Days of Bruges\u2013De Pa